Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to rapid increases in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community's Bureau of Statistics in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts showed only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the governing interest rate by saying that declining interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and declining unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter inflation" so that we do not have to intervene on this issue at a later time.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to rapid increases in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market odds have increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also rose considerably in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 percent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the inflation rate over 12 months remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the governing rate twice in 2008.
Gallup warns of government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Youth Democrats Alliance) increased significantly at the beginning of December, for example, since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, more than two-thirds (71 percent) support against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democrats’ Forum) and the SZDSZ (Free Democrats’ Alliance) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
Of some loyal voters going to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been so high, it is 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only one-tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of people surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, said the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of changing the political situation is the proportion of society that thinks discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, today this rate is only 20 per cent, and the relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of voting intention, 60 percent of respondents answered that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 percent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would likely participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be unquestionable.
74 per cent of people would say no to higher education enrolment fees, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 per cent would say no to hospital expenses.
When we look at only the same proportions among the people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital fees, respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has raised its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained last year’s average price increase of 16 percent, with the difference that this year’s VAT rate has not risen.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs commercial triangle, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, with a value increase of well over a thousand forints in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown" in major food stores in December, have no longer increased sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily shopping basket in the hypermarkets surveyed has exceeded the psychological threshold of at least 91 forints, at least ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this figure was 6,800 forints.)
Unicum and live fish prices have remained almost at last year's level, but turkey, walnut and poppy net prices have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics), but at Auchan, one kilogram of bread was found at only 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was astonishing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the record bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the record bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of his Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
When comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent gap while the difference between last year’s cheapest basket and this year’s most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process puzzled trade, as hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, they risk losing a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the lowest prices increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By bringing the two Christmas seasons closer together, we saw a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some basic foods, the Institute of Statistics found a price increase of more than 30 per cent over 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to make the sharp rise in prices also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-storage foods in pallets.
On Wednesday morning, major queues formed at the cash registers of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased abruptly.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less significant in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also make savings on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured man in a serious car accident was removed from the hospital but soon after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have been unable to perform a major operation because of the bacteria found in his body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National nosocomial surveillance system, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Namely, it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a bacterium well resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly patients, with low weight or with a weakened body.
According to János Hospital Principal Doctor, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
We must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we are not looking for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however infection can not always be prevented.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and seniors' homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these exams.
Most cases only emerge if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient care and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by droplet inhalation and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the contaminated patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable way or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, who had caused a fatal accident, was not drunk.
The official finding of the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd Arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, said Friday Attila Morvai, a spokeswoman for the public prosecution of the capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation that already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos street of the 22nd arrondissement.
(In fact, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Road Code a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and applied for retirement because, according to the police communication, the accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is conducted by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the outset with the magistrates tasked with conducting the investigation.
€400 million more for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Finance Minister, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on a €400 million credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, which has already been signed by the parties to a credit agreement of EUR 100 million. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million appropriation agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, with the remaining EUR 150 million to be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss possible changes to the initial contract when Hungary has finalized details of the metro’s financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and no commitment fee.
Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all of Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is still the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the area of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with shops and office spaces promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors already buy in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their life, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the edge of the Black Sea and in the most renowned ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle down buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old decayed houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, the proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term gains.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly rising due to increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian 6 per cent
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of professionals end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians arriving from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, intensive discussions are under way between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss exact figures, although it was willing to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from the 1990 level by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need, excluding emissions reductions.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors likely under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU’s ambition to maintain its role as flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent before 2020 from the level reached in 1990, regardless of the successful signing of the "post-2012 agreement", and is prepared to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries to the Kyoto Protocol had aimed at a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all the 15 EU members of that time made the commitment to 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent from the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, the press release of the Ministry of the Environment recalls.
The stake is big in Bali because the long-term international climate agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the values provided in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which the new IPCC has emphasized.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and an increase in Earth’s average temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
The British military units communicate, on the video-sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: special units intervening in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London where compatriots upload them on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" was watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as the "defenseheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and broadcasts videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the air force's original objective, the videos were posted on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make the general public aware of the actual objectives of the army's presence abroad.
Propaganda published in this way costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment ads on television, according to BBC Defence Consultant Gordon Mackenzie, but it also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the merits of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been passed on the sharing site which also show, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were made in real mission, but the British military has only recently been proud of the uploading of these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently by using the free downloadable America's Army shooting game. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
