The mega strike forces are gathering
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form, on Friday, their strike commission, which will be responsible for coordinating Monday's indefinite strike.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the Health Funds Act, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams because the rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and the employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The League Unions will announce, on Friday afternoon, the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike commission of LIGA - MOSZ will also be constituted, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protests will be held and, starting on Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the Health Funds Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Funds Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strikes.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide what action to take.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Funds Act will not take place until late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, major traffic jams are planned: railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning some of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies risk being stopped.
At the same time, in different parts of the country, half of the road will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strikes, the list of these is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organisations report striking for an indefinite period of time, while others have declared a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the M<0xC3><0x81>V (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) have not managed to reach an agreement on minimum services, but, as Christmas approaches, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 am and 9 am, the League Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union called to strike for 2 hours and 2 hours respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternately, the Union of Health and Social Sector Employees (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new conception to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new retirement calculation method to be implemented from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim seeks a guarantee, in the case of retirement before the legal age, that would allow to transfer into the system the functions that deserve it before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), attached to the League Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increased Country Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
In its "risk warning", the company points out that, in connection with the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur as a result of the exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsies and non-Gypsies in Hungary".
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's policy strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: “public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians”.
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and aggressive conflicts are more likely to occur, they say.
According to the research institute, due to the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially regarding the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following increased publicity on the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007, calling themselves the "national self-defense association".
“The common feature of these rallies is that they define themselves as a civilian organization while publicly declaring the preparation of their members for defence missions (catastrophes, national defense, defence of order), armies if necessary, in addition, by referring to the inadequacy of the police, the army, in other words the state,” they added.
They pointed out that everything was going according to the method that, based on the resentment of the society of politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions from a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil character and association status therefore serves only to avoid the legal pitfalls of the registration of these associations in court, but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk in relation to neighbouring relations.
In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and ultranationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This influences the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the constitution of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, political risks have increased across the region.
