The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and in the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the New Year's Eve can rest quietly.
In a year, we have eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national day, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, as is October 23, which is the commemorative day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1st is Labor Day and on November 1st and 2nd we remember the members of our family and our deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to rearrange working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the festival marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has been adjudicating in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and all their employees employed, public servants and persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions running without interruption and in service, because of their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because, according to experiences, the majority of people rather overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in the level of working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be rearranged for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25 will be a working day to have a day of rest on Friday, May 2.
Another change is scheduled for October 23: Saturday, October 18 will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
Six futile things that can terribly bother colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive, innocent lies that annoy us almost more: these are things that “beautify” the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether one gets used to these problems or takes up the challenge and consciously avoids ambiguous situations, causing trouble to others.
Examples.
“Excuse me, I forgot to tell you that you were called from the marketing department,” one colleague told you.
That you missed a date?
At best he is sorry and tries to fix things by calling the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to pass the message (this is the least common solution).
In most cases, this is arranged with apologies.
Before having painful explanations, it is worth thinking about how you can cause unpleasant moments to your colleagues and make efforts to avoid them.
Are you borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's nothing more annoying than wanting to take a file, an office tool or the phone and you can't find them anywhere.
Remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk but it disappeared the next morning?
Do you happen to find your pen that you thought was lost on your colleague's desk?
Don't take anything from your colleagues without asking, or they're right to be angry with you for stealing their good.
Do not bring back envelopes, post-it in your pocket because it can be annoying that there are no more and you need them right away.
Are you chatting about the privacy of colleagues?
There are no good ways to stop gossip spreading.
Who did what, with whom?
Or and why?
Don’t tell everyone your information (suppositions) about the privacy of your colleagues!
If a colleague shares his or her intimate secrets with you, don’t abuse his or her confidence!
Bury the shared information in yourself and do not discuss it with your colleagues in their absence even if your colleagues are also aware of it.
Are you saying you're sick for no reason?
When you call the office and declare yourself sick under the pretext of a heartbreaking headache because you feel sick or feel you need rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent affairs, your future missions must be done by someone else in your place.
Don't bother your colleagues!
If you know in advance that the next day you won’t go to work or that something might happen that would force you to stay at home, don’t forget to let your boss and colleagues know so they won’t be surprised at your absence the next day.
Roaring, scoffing, phone
You dive into your work but the scoffing of your colleagues suddenly rips you off?
Did you become, unwittingly, a witness of a phone conversation that you would have better not listened to?
Don’t bother your colleagues with humming, chanting, talking out loud (whatever you’re leading over their heads), kicking feet, rude words, or dissatisfaction expressed out loud.
They can bother even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, design, organization).
Are you accusing others of a mistake?
If your work is not done by the deadline, you forget to send an important mail or message, do not charge anyone for this forgetfulness!
Don’t put it on account of possible chaos in the office or your noisy colleagues!
Recognize it if you’ve made a mistake and if it’s inconvenient for others, fix it!
Ask how you could fix your fault, fix the negligence!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Putting on jogging and slippers is comfortable at home but they are not suitable for the office!
Don’t put on comfortable jogging even if your function allows it!
Do not be overlooked, respect your colleagues and yourself by dressing properly, and if your function requires it by putting on pretty and elegant clothes, to go to work!
