The Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales Valley to the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows there on limestone soil.
Mogotes, limestone balloons and rocks rise in candlelight from the bottom of the valley, and, since fertile soil has caught up in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetable carpet.
The valley is probably the place where Cuban tobacco of the highest quality is grown.
The final form of this product can be found if you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was shot.
