In Afghanistan, allies are passive, Americans say
The lack of troops and necessary equipment affects, according to the United States, the conduct of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission to Afghanistan is not going as it should, agreed in Edinburgh in Scotland representatives of countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
In addition to the growing protest by the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are also discussing future plans and coordination of allies.
While the U.S. this week, through Defense Minister Robert Gates, called NATO troops to greater activity, Britain sees as a priority the strengthening of the Afghan government’s authority and the intensification of development assistance.
“Evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defense Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents is, according to US military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 percent from last year, to 60 percent in the southern Helmand province.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
Now, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit and in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Specifically, they are asking for additional helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
“We will have to think seriously about concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them,” Gates said.
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop made similar comments today.
“I’m not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
