State debt to rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a debt of the state exceeding 84,000 crowns lies with each Czech.
The total debt rose at the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
The government planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
Thanks to better-than-expected government budget savings, the Department has reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The debt of the state of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
During the nine months of this year it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, as of June, it decreased by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on the debt of the State in early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns lies with each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has indebted more than 111 billion crowns.
"For now, it appears that, thanks to a smaller deficit projected for next year, we could cross the border by one trillion crowns only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor's forecast is similar: "We could exceed the trillion in 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that we do not yet know.
If it appeared that the situation on the political scene was changing, that policies were willing to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I’m not expecting that change,” he said.
Debts are Growing
The debt of the state is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated mainly by the accumulation of deficits of the state budget.
Government debt is financed by treasury bills, bonds, direct loans or by borrowing from the European Investment Bank, for example.
The state's domestic debt has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The state’s external debt has so far increased this year from 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion crowns.
The debt of the state called negotiable reached at the end of September 803.3 billion crowns and from the month of June it decreased by 13.7 billion crowns.
The average debt liability of the State was 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased year-on-year from the first to the third half of the year by 13 percent, which, given the current good health of the economy, is far too high.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
