Better than we expected
This follows the 2007 State Debt Financing and Management Strategy, which the government planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution in the savings of the state budget, the ministry reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The amount is essentially constituted by the deficit in the state budget, which is clearly going to reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the originally planned 91.3 billion crowns.
Second, the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency are 13.3 billion crowns, the 10 billion reserve for pension payments, the financing of government bonds for 43 billion crowns and the repayments of the European Investment Bank's loans of 1.8 billion crowns.
She was in court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear.
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and to deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting pupils ages 6 to 7 give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punished with whips.
The 54-year-old British teacher at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with attacking Islam and sedition under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when the teacher asked her 6-7-year-old students to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
“Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the caption “My name is Mohamed”.
The bear itself did not carry any label with that name, but the problem is simply that of the representation of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that might be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he said it was only an "innocent mistake."
The opinion shared by many of the teacher's pupils who describe her as "very caring for her pupils" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Remember that the first name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the Prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
For example, can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on Wednesday on the future status of the province, at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians concluded a sixth and final discussion session in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is unfortunate that the parties were unable to reach an agreement on the status," European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region was “at stake,” his U.S. counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to abide by their commitments to preserving peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
“We do not anticipate violence immediately, but we are entering a very difficult time,” he added, noting that “obvious tensions exist.”
End of mediation on December 10
The mediators of the troika, which brings together the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90 percent-albanophone province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian ombudsman Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was tasked with further mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans believe that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo at the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” Botsan-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, Westerners believe that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina said she was ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council did not decide in her favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," Kosovo's president Fatmir Sejdiu said at the hotel in Baden, where the "last chance negotiations" had been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade “belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations.”
‘domino effect’
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still feasible, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
Belgrade said it feared a "domino effect" in a region still fragile by the independence wars of the 1990s.
“For Serbia,” he said, “this does not mean that a compromise is impossible.”
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision be made exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto.
“The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word”
“Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia,” Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
“These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.”
Fatmir Sedjiu told reporters that “the Kosovo Parliament will have the final say on the status,” adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by Albanian speakers would be made “in consultation” with Westerners.
Bush torn a deal between Israelis and Palestinians
President George W. Bush announced at the opening of the international peace conference he met Tuesday in Annapolis, Maryland, that the Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately begin negotiations with a view to reaching a final settlement of the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do anything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, Palestinians must dismantle “terrorist infrastructure” and Israel must end its colonization activities, Bush said, recalling both sides to their obligations under the “roadmap” for peace they agreed to in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority presided over by Abbas would aim "to conclude a peace treaty resolving all outstanding issues, without exception, including core issues".
