A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are openly accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his descendants.
The eleven states responsible for managing them - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all States was completed, the opening had been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out “in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, had objected to the opening to the public of such personal documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subject to compulsory labour and, eventually, to provide proof of their detention, in order to pave the way for compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
