The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Law, involves the modernization of the financial markets, at a time when it strengthens the protection of the investor, improves the powers of the leaders of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the different leaders of the European Union.
The new regulation will provide financial advisory services for both specialized corporate and legal reasons and creates a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial advisory companies (FIBs), which merge with securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it increases the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that it is possible to add to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and order internationalization systems, which face competition from existing stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment firms to disclose information on the market on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and forms of risk management and obliges them to keep a record of all transactions they carry out, to facilitate control on the part of the CNMV.
Passing through the Congressional Economic Commission, several amendments have been added, including one that highlights that securitised debt will be considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated with what happened with U.S. high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
