The new gas case between Russia and Ukraine is setting off the alarm.
A dispute over the price of gas is fermenting between Ukraine and Russia, thus increasing the risk of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are carried by pipelines, and each pipeline is carefully monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two caused a decrease in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia’s proprietary monopoly company providing the gas, tried in vain to reach an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as expected, given that it agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would mean for Ukraine a 40% increase in import costs from Gazprom.
“It is essential for us to use all of our arguments during the conversations, reminding us that we are a country through which most of the gas passes,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters.
“The fluctuations in gas costs would probably be linked to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.”
The last major altercation between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006 caused the interruption of Gazprom supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, resulting in higher prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU’s supplies.
Russia has the largest gas stockpiles, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
