Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and whirlwinds at the poles, similar to those that appear on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning strikes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today has proved this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning flashes on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprine, lightning has reportedly made life appear on Earth: the storm has allegedly stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life was there, it must have been at a very early date in history," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes with temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the Earth’s infernal twin, but it remains a twin,” Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of Venus Express in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venusian research, as no spacecraft had been on the way for exploration of the planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the latest research results that have now been presented in several papers in "Nature" do not only highlight the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the Earth’s common ground on our neighboring planet is more numerous than initially assumed.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the already known wind whirls at the North Pole, a whirlwind of clouds at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called an evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much slower on itself: one Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
