These aren't Warhol's boxes.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
Much of the ninety "Type Stockholm" Brillo-Boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago questioned the authenticity of the "Brillo-Boxes of the Year" of Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today results in a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum gave the "Brillo-Boxes of the Year" to the international moderna Museet in 1995.
Ancient history is entangled, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden cases, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 presented - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cartoning factory.
These were not works of art here, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some wooden cases produced by Brillo in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time were said to have entered the history of art and auctions, as authorized original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum later wrongly claimed that about one hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol later ceded to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied to the laminated panels without a bottom layer, using a paint roll - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic one.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet's collection will classify all six boxes into one.
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
The rebel soldiers of Manila abandon
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers abandoned, the same ones who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not be held responsible for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to the power had stormed the hotel shortly before using tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
Approximately half of them were standing in court on Wednesday over a failed coup attempt in 2003 - including Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 supporters.
The military police, who were normally to monitor them, apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal troops in power circled the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have had enough,” Trillanes said.
“We are calling people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who commanded before the Scout Rangers' elite unit, said other army units would soon want to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already the scene of the mutiny attempt by some 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke down nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes a major shareholder of Versatel.
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 percent in telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as reported by the company on Wednesday.
Only 20.05 percent of the share capital would be held.
We had previously speculated on a buyout.
The option would remain open to further increase the stake in Versatel.
This step is aimed at accelerating the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Just before, assumptions had already been made on Wednesday about an entry, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf network operator from 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The credit institution would hold the money only for a third party, the market is told.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired a nearly 10 percent stake in mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth €106.4 million on the stock exchange.
United Internet bought 5.15 million for 31.1 million euros.
In addition, the companies have opened negotiations on cooperation in the marketing of DSL and mobile phone products.
“We are strengthening our partnership,” a United Internet spokesman said.
The two companies founded the MSP holding company in order to absorb competitor Freenet.
At the moment, the two companies want to be satisfied with their ten percent stake in Freenet, and not to make use of their right to endorse an additional 18.49 percent at Freenet, United Internet said Thursday.
However, the two companies would leave all options open, particularly to increase the stake in SA Freenet, it was learned.
Negotiations between United Internet and Freenet over a strategic partnership ended in mid-October.
The hardly predictable poker on Freenet that has lasted for months is part of the consolidation of the German telecoms market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million customers linked to a mobile phone contract and 1.27 million DSL and full subscription customers.
The Holding of United Internet and Drillisch had so far held a 6.01 percent direct stake in Freenet.
It was now agreed that Drillisch would bring an additional four percent.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent of investment company Vatas had already been decided in August.
